<TITLE> Old rivals fight for presidency in Maldives runoff </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Male, Oct 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Two old rivals squared off in a presidential runoff in the Maldives on Tuesday, in which Asia's longest-serving leader faced a unified opposition for the first time in his 30-year rule over the tropical Indian Ocean islands. Voting started shortly after 9 a.m. (0400 GMT) in the historic election, which came after President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom failed to secure 50 percent of the vote in the archipelago nation's first multiparty elections on Oct. 9-10. Gayoom, 71, now faces Mohamed "Anni" Nasheed, a democracy activist his government has jailed 27 times, who has the backing of the four other candidates who stood in the first-round poll. The vote is the culmination of years of agitation for democratic reforms on the string of 1,192 mostly uninhabited coral atolls 800 km (500 miles) off the tip of India. The Maldives is best-known as a tropical idyll of azure waters and Robinson Crusoe-like solitude, frequented by Hollywood stars and those who can afford room rates rising to thousands of dollars a night
